Q8. Find fun(4).
int fun(int n)
{
    if(n<=1)
        return 1;

    return fun(n-1)+fun(n-1);
}

Ans. 
f(0)=1
f(1)=1
f(2)=2
f(3)=4
f(4)=8

Q9. Find fib(6)
int fib(int n)
{
    if(n<=1)
        return n;

    return fib(n-1)+fib(n-2);
}

Ans. 0 1 1 2 3 5 8

Q10. Maximum stack depth for fun(100)?
void fun(int n)
{
    if(n==0)
        return;

    fun(n-1);
}

Ans. 101
Calls from 100 down to 0

Q11. Find fun(5)
int fun(int n)
{
    if(n==1)
        return 1;

    return n*fun(n-1);
}

Ans. 5×4×3×2×1 = 120

Q12. #include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void change(int &x)
{
    x = 50;
}

int main()
{
    int a = 10;
    change(a);
    cout << a;
}

Ans.  x becomes another name for a
a → 10
x → same memory location

so, x=50 then
a also beomes 50

Q13. Which is Tail Recursive?
A) return n*fun(n-1);
B) return fun(n-1);
C) return fun(n-1)+1;
D) return fun(n-1)+fun(n-2);

Ans. B
Tail recursion means the recursive call must be the last operation performed.
here, Nothing remains after the recursive call.

Q14. Find fun(16)
int fun(int n)
{
    if(n==1)
        return 0;

    return 1 + fun(n/2);
}

Ans. fun(16)
= 1 + fun(8)
= 1 + 1 + fun(4)
= 1 + 1 + 1 + fun(2)
= 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + fun(1)
= 4

The function counts how many times n can be divided by 2 before reaching 1.

Q15. What is the output of the following C++ program?
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
void fun(int n, int &x)
{
    if(n <= 0)
        return;
    x++;
    fun(n - 1, x);
    x++;
}
int main()
{
    int a = 0;
    fun(3, a);
    cout << a;
    return 0;
}

Ans. 6
The parameter x is passed by reference.
Therefore, every modification of x directly changes the original variable a